    <div class="col-md-12">
        <p> Furthermore, the journey took us past several rice and corn fields, pineapple and watermelon plantations and of course many palm trees with coconuts. Everything was sold by local residents on the side of the road and at such low prices that you would like to take everything with you. And then we approached the Hills over the town of Carmen. Incidentally, the Chocolate Hills are not made by any creative person, but were created only by nature many thousands of years ago. It is approximately 1,200 up to 120 m high cone -shaped hills. These are overgrown with ferns and meadows and look out of palm forests at the top. In late summer the hills dye brown, then this looks like a giant pack of chocolates. </p>
        <p> It was "more tourist" around us and then we already turned in on the left, past many souvenir shops and drove up one of the hills. The driver pressed us a piece of paper and his license plate, explained that we should let the man know over there and he would come up again to collect us. We were a little confused, undecided whether we have to pay admission or what else and so we first took pictures of the area behind the shop. There you could already see some of the hills! Despite several clouds, the sun burned quite a bit and so we went into the snack bar and also saw that we have to pay "admission". You can't actually call this admission, because you simply pay the fee for the vehicle. So the note from our driver! </p>
    </div>

