    <div class="col-md-6">
        <p> Fee of 50 peso per nose (approx. 80 cents) paid and then it was called 214 steps upwards at monkey heat. Fortunately, it wasn't that much going on, so we could enjoy the view and take pictures. Unfortunately, the sun burned so badly that we quickly searched the shadow and made our way down again quickly. There we briefly dawned through the souvenir shops until we stopped the restaurant chilled in the air conditioning systems and drank something first. Then it went back into the heat and Basti had the driver called. </p>
        <p> Back in the car it went down and since I had not yet found a chic shirt, the driver stopped again at the foot of the hill. Unfortunately, I didn't find what I was looking for here either and so the journey continued. This time we landed in the task, or also called Koboldmakis. These are small (max. 16 cm), nocturnal monkeys living on Bohol. Unfortunately, almost not at all in the wild, so the journey took us to the "Tasier Conservation Area" in Loboc. So far I only knew the "Tasier Sanctury" in Corella from the Internet, so I was excited to see what awaited me here. We once again solved a laughing entry of less than 100 peso (&euro; 1.70) per nose and off we went. We were there shortly before the end of the day and so there wasn't much going on. Everything was really very dilapidated and in conversion or simply untidy and the question arose how to find these tiny animals. </p>
    </div>

    <div class="col-md-12">
        <p> Then we saw an employee a little further. These are always exactly where an animal is sitting, otherwise you would mercilessly walk past the animals. In addition, the employees also take care that visitors do not get too close to the animals. In the end we were maybe 20 minutes on the premises and saw 9 animals that almost hidden in the branches. </p>
        <p> The next stop was the Loboc River. The way there led us through the man -made mahogany forest, where some people stood on the side of the road and took photos. It continued through some hairpin curves down to the river. There should be a boat trip including buffet for us. Fix the 550 peso (&euro; 8.50) p. Person paid and we were already able to go on the boat and were accompanied to a table. I looked around at the buffet and found it good and sufficient. So far I haven't been so hungry, but the buffet changed it very quickly. There were also two musicians on board and entertained us while driving. Although it was relatively narrow on the boat, everything went relaxed and even led us past locals who made their laundry in the river or just splashed in the water. Then we put on a stop and were entertained by locals with traditional singing and dance performance. At the "end" of the navigable Loboc River we also saw the adventure park, where the Zipline carries out. This is a kind of cable car, only that you are strapped in lying down and flies across tree tops and river. </p>
    </div>

    <div class="col-md-6">
        <p> We turned and it went back when the pineapple and watermelon were eaten. Meanwhile, Basti tried the Filipino milk coffee variant - consisting of coconut jelly with coffee taste in milk. Arrived again at the investor, we went to one of the Souvenir Shops again and I finally found a shirt! Unfortunately it was late, so we already thought that we had to drop the butterfly station, since everything closes very early here. On the car, our driver told us that we are now heading for them. Cool! </p>
        <p> The journey did not take very long and shortly afterwards we ended up in the butterfly facility, but somehow it looked different when I knew it from the Internet. And then I already saw the signs at the entrance that we were elsewhere. I also read posters from giant phytons etc. here, but since I wasn't interested, I had not selected this as a goal when planning the travel. We had landed at the "XzooTic Animal Park"! </p>
        <p> Admission was laughable again and so we went in and made a damn big mistake without knowing it until then. A young Filipino accompanied us and started explaining things and advertising for the snakes. But we absolutely wanted to see the butterflies and headed for them. </p>
    </div>

